### 2. Scaling Duplication Detection

Naive token-based clone detection compares every token sequence to every other, resulting in $O(N^2)$ complexity. For a 10M LOC codebase (~50 million tokens), this requires quadrillions of comparisons, which will permanently stall a pipeline. We must transition to sub-quadratic algorithms:

**1. Suffix Arrays (with Longest Common Prefix - LCP)**

* **Algorithm:** Builds a sorted array of all suffixes in the concatenated token stream. Can find all maximal exact matches.
* **Complexity:** $O(N)$ time (via SA-IS algorithm), $O(N)$ space.
* **Implementation & Constants:** Extremely high implementation complexity and brutal memory constants. An integer suffix array plus an LCP array requires 12–16 bytes per token. For 50M tokens, this burns ~600-800MB of contiguous RAM just for the index, causing heavy cache-miss penalties and risking Out-Of-Memory (OOM) kills on small CI workers.

**2. Locality Sensitive Hashing (LSH) / MinHash**

* **Algorithm:** Breaks code into AST function nodes, extracts token n-grams, and computes a fixed-size MinHash signature. Groups signatures into LSH bands to find candidate pairs.
* **Complexity:** $O(N)$ time to generate signatures, $O(1)$ expected lookup for collisions.
* **Implementation & Constants:** Moderate complexity. High CPU constant (computing hash permutations), but remarkably low memory footprint. A 1,000-line function reduces to a ~256-byte signature. Best for detecting Type-3 (fuzzy) clones where developers copy-pasted and heavily modified variable names.

**3. Inverted Indexes with Winnowing (Rolling Hashes)**

* **Algorithm:** Slides a window of $W$ tokens, computing an $O(1)$ Rabin-Karp rolling hash. To prevent storing a hash for every token, the *Winnowing* algorithm selects only the minimum hash in every local window of size $K$. Surviving hashes are stored in an inverted index map (`Hash -> List[File_Locations]`).
* **Complexity:** $O(N)$ time, $O(N/K)$ space.
* **Implementation & Constants:** Low complexity. Incredibly fast CPU constants (integer hashing) and tunable, bounded memory limits.

**Optimal Architecture:** Use **Winnowing** for structural, exact-block clone detection due to its speed and low memory footprint. Optionally run **LSH** strictly at the function level for fuzzy clone detection.

